""desc"": ""   In the late 19th century, a chilling tale unfolded in the dark corners of Transylvania, introducing the world to one of the most iconic figures of horror literature—the vampire Count Dracula. The story begins with a young English lawyer named Jonathan Harker, who was sent to Transylvania to assist Count Dracula in the purchase of an estate in London. As Harker ventured deeper into the Carpathian Mountains, he couldn't shake off an eerie feeling that something sinister lurked in the shadows. Upon arriving at Castle Dracula, Harker found himself in the presence of a mysterious and enigmatic nobleman. Count Dracula was a tall, pale figure with sharp features and a commanding presence. Harker soon discovered that his host possessed supernatural abilities and an insatiable thirst for human blood.
 
   As days turned into nights, Harker became a virtual prisoner in the castle, subjected to the Count's relentless and terrifying presence. He uncovered the truth about Dracula—he was an immortal vampire who sustained his existence by preying upon the living.Meanwhile, back in England, Harker's fiancée Mina Murray, along with her best friend Lucy Westenra, found themselves entangled in a web of darkness. Lucy, a vibrant and beautiful young woman, fell victim to the Count's insidious powers and became one of the undead. Distraught over Lucy's transformation, her suitors—Arthur Holmwood, Dr. John Seward, and Quincey Morris—joined forces with the renowned Dutch vampire hunter Abraham Van Helsing. Together, they sought to rid London of the vampire's menace and save Lucy's soul.Van Helsing, armed with knowledge of vampire lore, deduced that Count Dracula was the source of Lucy's affliction. The group embarked on a perilous quest to track down the vampire and put an end to his reign of terror.
 
   Their pursuit led them to the dark alleys of London, where they faced numerous challenges and encounters with the supernatural. Van Helsing guided the group, equipping them with crucifixes, wooden stakes, and sacred relics to aid in their fight against the forces of evil. As the battle between good and evil intensified, Count Dracula sought to expand his dominion and find new victims. His menacing presence and ability to control wolves and bats heightened the sense of dread and danger that loomed over the city. Throughout their harrowing journey, the group discovered Dracula's vulnerability to sunlight, crucifixes, and the sacred soil of his homeland. Armed with this knowledge, they hatched a plan to destroy the vampire and save Mina, who had also fallen under Dracula's spell.
 
   In a climactic showdown, the group cornered Dracula in his own lair, confronting him with their arsenal of weapons. Van Helsing, armed with a sacred knife, struck the final blow, piercing the vampire's heart and ending his reign of terror. With Dracula defeated, Lucy and the other victims of his curse found peace in death. Mina, having escaped the vampire's clutches, was finally freed from his influence. The group, exhausted but triumphant, vowed to protect others from the horrors they had witnessed. 
   The legacy of Dracula endures, captivating audiences with its depiction of a malevolent creature of the night. The story serves as a reminder that even in the face of darkness, courage and unity can overcome evil. Count Dracula's legend remains etched in our collective imagination—a symbol of both terror and fascination with the unknown.""

""desc"": ""   In the bustling city of Florence, during the early 16th century, there lived a young woman named Lisa Gherardini. Lisa was known for her striking beauty and enigmatic charm, which captivated all who encountered her. Little did she know that her portrait would one day become the most famous and enigmatic painting in the world—the Mona Lisa. Lisa grew up in a modest family, and at the age of sixteen, she married a wealthy Florentine merchant named Francesco del Giocondo. Lisa became known as Mona Lisa, meaning ""Madam Lisa,"" a title of respect given to married women in Italian society.
   In 1503, the renowned Italian artist Leonardo da Vinci received a commission from Francesco del Giocondo to paint a portrait of his wife. Leonardo, known for his artistic genius and innovative techniques, gladly accepted the task. Little did he know that this painting would become his most celebrated masterpiece. As Leonardo began to work on the portrait, he discovered that Mona Lisa possessed a unique aura—an aura that he was determined to capture on canvas. He observed her every feature, from her enigmatic smile to the depths of her soulful eyes. Leonardo's meticulous attention to detail and his ability to capture the essence of his subjects allowed him to bring Mona Lisa to life. For years, Leonardo devoted himself to the painting, working tirelessly to perfect every brushstroke and nuance. He experimented with various techniques, using sfumato to create soft transitions between colors and chiaroscuro to achieve depth and realism. The result was a portrait that seemed to radiate with a quiet, timeless beauty.
   Leonardo's depiction of Mona Lisa was unlike any other portrait of its time. Instead of the rigid, formal poses commonly seen in Renaissance art, Mona Lisa appeared relaxed and natural. Her enigmatic smile sparked curiosity and fascination among those who viewed the painting. Despite its remarkable qualities, the Mona Lisa did not garner much attention during Leonardo's lifetime. The artist kept the portrait with him until his death in 1519. After his passing, the painting passed through various hands, eventually finding its way into the possession of King Francis I of France. Under the French monarchy, the Mona Lisa gained recognition and began to captivate the imaginations of art enthusiasts. Its mystery, the depth of its subject's expression, and the masterful technique employed by Leonardo made it an object of intrigue and admiration.
   In 1911, however, the painting was stolen from the Louvre Museum in Paris, causing a worldwide sensation. The theft catapulted the Mona Lisa to even greater fame, as newspapers and art lovers across the globe mourned the loss of the iconic masterpiece. After an extensive search, the painting was recovered in 1913 and returned to its rightful place in the Louvre, where it remains today, protected and revered. The Mona Lisa continues to captivate millions of visitors each year. People from all corners of the globe travel to the Louvre to catch a glimpse of her enigmatic smile and gaze into her timeless eyes. Countless interpretations and theories have emerged, attempting to unravel the secrets hidden within the painting, but the true meaning of Mona Lisa's expression remains a subject of debate and speculation. Whether it is the mastery of Leonardo's technique, the mystery surrounding the subject, or the fascination with the painting's history, the Mona Lisa holds an undeniable allure. She is a symbol of beauty, intrigue, and the enduring power of art to transcend time.
   The story of Mona Lisa, the woman behind the captivating smile, may forever remain shrouded in mystery. Yet, her image continues to inspire awe and wonder, reminding us of the profound impact that art can have on our lives. The Mona Lisa stands as a testament to the artistic brilliance of Leonardo da Vinci and the enduring power of an enigmatic smile that has captured the hearts of millions throughout the ages.""

""desc"": ""   In the small village of Domrémy, nestled in the heart of France, a young girl named Joan was born in the year 1412. Joan was a spirited and devout child, known for her piety and her strong sense of righteousness. Little did she know that she would become one of the most remarkable figures in French history—the legendary Joan of Arc. At the time of Joan's birth, France was embroiled in a bitter conflict known as the Hundred Years' War, a long-standing battle between the French and the English. The French monarchy was divided, and the English had taken control of large parts of the country, including the capital, Paris. Joan, however, harbored a deep love for her country and believed that she was destined to save France from its plight. She began to experience visions and hear divine voices, which she identified as saints and angels. These celestial messengers instructed her to take up arms and lead the French army to victory.
   Driven by her unwavering faith and her sense of purpose, Joan decided to approach the dauphin, the uncrowned heir to the French throne, Charles VII. Disguised as a man, she traveled to the dauphin's court at Chinon and requested an audience. Initially skeptical of the young peasant girl, Charles VII agreed to meet with Joan. To test her, he disguised himself among his courtiers. But Joan, guided by her visions, was able to identify him instantly. This miraculous feat convinced Charles VII of her divine mission, and he granted her an army. Clad in armor and carrying a banner with the image of the Virgin Mary, Joan led the French forces into battle. Despite her lack of military training, her presence and unwavering faith inspired her troops, and they experienced a series of victories. The tides of the war began to turn, as the French reclaimed territories that had been under English control for years.
   Joan's most iconic triumph came during the siege of Orléans, a strategic city on the banks of the Loire River. The English army had laid siege to Orléans for months, and the city was on the brink of collapse. Joan, filled with determination, led a daring assault that caught the English off guard. Her strategic brilliance and unwavering courage drove the English forces back, leading to the liberation of Orléans. News of Joan's victories spread throughout France and Europe, and her reputation as a miraculous warrior grew. However, her success also attracted the attention of her enemies. In May 1430, Joan was captured by the Burgundians, allies of the English, during a skirmish near Compiègne. Joan was handed over to the English, who saw her as a threat and an obstacle to their control over France. She was put on trial for charges of heresy and witchcraft. Despite the lack of evidence, Joan was found guilty and sentenced to death. On May 30, 1431, at the age of just nineteen, Joan of Arc was burned at the stake in Rouen. Her death shook the nation and sparked outrage among those who saw her as a symbol of hope and liberation. Her bravery and unwavering faith in the face of adversity left an indelible mark on French history.
   Decades later, Joan's trial was reexamined, and she was posthumously declared innocent of all charges. She was canonized as a saint by the Catholic Church in 1920, and she remains an enduring symbol of French patriotism and female empowerment.
   The story of Joan of Arc serves as a testament to the power of faith, courage, and conviction. Joan's unwavering belief in her divine mission and her determination to fight for her country against all odds continue to inspire people around the world to this day. Her legacy as the Maid of Orléans lives on, reminding us that even the most unlikely of heroes can change the course of history.""

The dystopian version of superintelligence is illustrated with frequency by leaders in the technology industry, and is famously depicted by Hollywood in films like Terminator, or more recently Ex Machina, and even the Avengers. The “angry god A.I.” is a story you know, because it is the story you are constantly told: we build the thinking machine, it surpasses our abilities in every way, and it destroys us for one of any number of reasons.
Maybe it perceives us as a threat. Maybe we’re just in its way, and it hardly perceives us at all — humanity, a disposable insect race.

There are of course many arguments in opposition to the now ubiquitous concept of our apocalypse by artificial intelligence. I myself have called into question the logic of such dystopian arguments in Anatomy of Next. But our subject here is less pertaining to the nature of the conscious machine than it is to the way we talk about this subject, and what it means. First, consider that most of the artificial intelligence depicted in culture looks human, a representation with no basis in technological reality. Then, the true scope of the Singularity is almost impossible to predict, which begs a question: where are these opinions about the broadly unknowable coming from?
